%I A397306 #15 Jul 06 2026 12:15:49
%S A397306 4,5,6,10,17,18,29,34,41,53,59,65,66,89,97,119,130,137,163,179,185,
%T A397306 191,193,209,217,219,221,223,233,239,247,253,258,269,281,305,307,311,
%U A397306 343,359,389,403,407,415,419,427,431,457,491,505,514,521,533,545,547,557,569,575,581
%N A397306 Positive numbers m such that m - 2^k is a prime for exactly one value of k > 0 with 2^k < m.
%C A397306 With r(m) = #{k > 0 : 2^k < m, m-2^k is prime}, this sequence gives terms satisfying r(m) = 1.
%C A397306 When m is even, then m-2^k is even for all k>0; as the only even prime is 2, necessarily, subsequence of even terms correspond to A052548 \ {3}.
%C A397306 Subsequence of odd terms is A283806 \ {3} (see example section).
%F A397306 Equals (Union of A052548 and A283806) \ {3}.
%e A397306 3 is not a term because 3-2^1 = 1 that is not prime.
%e A397306 18 is a term since: 18-2=16, 18-4=14, 18-8=10, 18-16=2, and only 2 is prime.
%e A397306 29 is a term since: 29-2=27, 29-4=25, 29-8=21, 29-16=13, and only 13 is prime.
%t A397306 q[m_] := Sum[Boole[PrimeQ[m-2^k]], {k, 1, Floor[Log2[m]]}] == 1; Select[Range[600], q] (* _Amiram Eldar_, Jun 29 2026 *)
%Y A397306 Cf. A039669, A052548, A283806, A397305.
%K A397306 nonn,new
%O A397306 1,1
%A A397306 _Bernard Schott_, Jun 28 2026
